# Keep `README.md` in sync with feature changes

`README.md` is the project's **high-level functional spec** (companion to
`docs/SPEC.md`, which holds the exhaustive as-built log). When a strand
changes user-observable behaviour, `README.md` must be updated in the same
commit.

## Trigger

Update `README.md` when a strand adds, removes, or modifies anything in:

- **§2 Core features** — the kiosk's behaviour, node kinds, animations,
  routing, import/export, version handling.
- **§3 Architecture at a glance** — the Lit custom-element table, the
  hexagonal layer map, or any new top-level directory under `src/`.
- **§4 Tech stack** — adding/removing a runtime or build-time dependency.
- **§5 Development** — adding/renaming an npm script the user is expected
  to run.
- **§7 Documentation map** — new docs or renamed/retired ones.

## Skip when

- Pure internal refactor that doesn't change user-visible behaviour or the
  public surface (`src/main.ts` composition + the Lit element catalogue).
- Planning-only strands (NO TS code; SPEC §17.80 / §17.82 / §17.94 pattern).
- `sonar.projectVersion` bumps, leak-baseline resets, lint-config tweaks.

## Procedure

1. Edit the relevant section(s) of `README.md` in the **same commit** as
   the feature change. Do NOT defer to a follow-up.
2. Keep the README **functional**, not implementation-detail (those go in
   `docs/SPEC.md`).
3. If a new Lit custom element ships, add a row to the §3 table.
4. If a new npm script ships, add a line under §5.

## Example

A strand that adds a `<my-new-modal>` Lit element accessible from the
burger menu:

- `docs/SPEC.md` — append the full as-built row in the §17.0 table.
- `README.md` — add `<my-new-modal>` to the §3 table AND mention the new
  burger-menu entry under §2 (Core features → Editing).
